        <div class="sec-head">
          <span class="tag tag-dim" style="margin-bottom:16px;display:inline-flex;">Trust note</span>
          <h2 id="trust-h" style="font-size:clamp(28px,4vw,40px);">The December 2024 pricing event — what happened</h2>
          <p style="font-size:17px;color:var(--text-3);max-width:640px;">No honest Tidio review can skip this. It's the single biggest reason cited in negative G2 and Capterra reviews through 2026 and it materially affects the trust calculation for new buyers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="body-text" style="max-width:740px;">
          <p>In December 2024, Tidio implemented a major pricing restructure that effectively doubled monthly bills for many existing customers. Documented cases on G2 and Capterra describe customers seeing their charges jump from approximately $32/month to $64/month, with reports of automatic credit card charges processing before customers had time to review or cancel.</p>

          <p>The change was widely characterised as a "bait and switch" in user reviews — customers had committed to a pricing model that was changed unilaterally. Trustpilot and Reddit threads from late 2024 and early 2025 are full of churned-customer accounts. The trust impact persists into 2026 reviews.</p>

          <p><strong>What this means for new buyers in 2026:</strong></p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Don't sign annual contracts immediately.</strong> Stay on monthly billing for 60-90 days minimum to validate the platform and watch for any pricing announcements. The annual discount (~17-20%) isn't worth the lock-in until you've confirmed Tidio fits your store.</li>
            <li><strong>Monitor announcement channels.</strong> Tidio's pricing page, in-product announcements, and your account email — check periodically. The 2024 event hit hardest among customers who weren't paying close attention.</li>
            <li><strong>Have a migration plan ready.</strong> Know which alternative you'd switch to if pricing changes again. Gorgias for larger stores. Reamaze for per-agent simplicity. Crisp or Chatra for solo founders.</li>
            <li><strong>Free plan users are unaffected.</strong> If you're on the free tier, this doesn't apply to you — you're not paying anything to be doubled.</li>
          </ul>

          <p>None of this means Tidio is a bad product — Lyro AI genuinely works, the Shopify integration is clean, and the conversation-based pricing model is rational for the right size store. But the trust event is real and ongoing, and any honest review has to flag it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
